Demand Forecasting for a Fast-Food Restaurant Chain¶

Data Modelling: Please see Appendix 1¶

Overview of dataset¶

This forecats is based solely of the daily demand of lettuce from 06/03/2019 - 15/06/2019, no other contributing factors were used within the forecast.

We can see through the histogram and density plot that the sample values do not have a clear bell shape curve indicating some disproportionate balance of values. from math import sqrt
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

def rmse_measure(actual, forecast):
    forecast = np.exp(forecast)
    actual = np.exp(actual)
    rms = sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual,forecast))
    return round(rms,2)



rmse1 = rmse_measure(testset_h,for1)
rmse2 = rmse_measure(testset_h,for2)
rmse3 = rmse_measure(testset_h,for3)
rmse4 = rmse_measure(testset_h,for4)
rmse5 = rmse_measure(testset_h,for1d)
rmse6 = rmse_measure(testset_h,for2d)
rmse7 = rmse_measure(testset_h,for3d)
rmse8 = rmse_measure(testset_h,for4d)



print("rmse1: " + str(rmse1) + " rmse2 "+str(rmse2)," rmse3 "+str(rmse3)," rmse4 "+str(rmse4)," rmse5 "+str(rmse5)," rmse6 "+str(rmse6)," rmse7 "+str(rmse7)," rmse8 "+str(rmse8))

ARIMA Model¶

We observed a moderate trend and seasonality through the decomposition of the time series so in order for it to be stationery we will need some order of differencing. Let us first take the stationery tests on the original time series to verify the series is non-stationery:

Time series split - original series¶

As the requirement is to forecast for the next two weeks we define the splitpoint as 14.

def rolling_plot(timeseries):
    #Determine Rolling Stats
    rolmean = timeseries.rolling(7).mean()
    rolstd = timeseries.rolling(7).std()

    #Plot
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
    orig = plt.plot(timeseries, color='blue', label ='original')
    mean = plt.plot(rolmean, color='red', label ='rolling_7_day_mean')
    std = plt.plot(rolstd, color='black', label ='rolling_7_day_variance')
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.title("Rolling Mean & Standard Deviation")
    plt.show()

rolling_plot(trainset_a)

Still some change in the mean and variance over time so will use stationery checks to confirm if series is stationery

Stationarize the data¶

Stationery Tests¶

ADF Test Null Hypothesis (H0): The time series is non-stationery meaning that it has some time dependent structure.

Remove Seasonality¶

I used a polynomial of high degree eg.8 to fit the series and approximate the seasonality identified within the decomposition.I then remove this component for the original trainset series and I obtain the deaseasonalised series.

In [93]:
from pandas import read_csv
from matplotlib import pyplot
from numpy import polyfit
series = trainset_a
# fit polynomial: x^2*b1 + x*b2 + ... + bn
X = [i%7 for i in range(0, len(series))]
y = series.values
degree = 8
coef = polyfit(X, y, degree)
print('Coefficients: %s' % coef)
# create curve
curve = list()
for i in range(len(X)):
	value = coef[-1]
	for d in range(degree):
		value += X[i]**(degree-d) * coef[d]
	curve.append(value)
# create seasonally adjusted
values = series.values
diff = list()
for i in range(len(values)):
	value = values[i] - curve[i]
	diff.append(value)
pyplot.plot(diff)
pyplot.show()
pyplot.plot(curve)
pyplot.plot(series)

Differencing¶

Trend was identified in the decomposition I will remove this trend with level 1 differncing:

In [95]:
def difference(dataset, diff_value):
    diff = list()
    for i in range(diff_value, len(dataset)):
        value = dataset[i] - dataset[i - diff_value]
        diff.append(value)
    return Series(diff)

diff1 = difference(diff,1)

pyplot.plot(diff1)
pyplot.show()

result = seasonal_decompose(diff1,model = 'additive',freq=7)

Performance Comparison between Holts-Winter & ARIMA¶

Both forecasts are biased as there remains some correlation within the residuals as neither have a mean of zero. The mean for the ARIMA forecast residuals is closer to zero indicating that there is less unexplained variation of the data in the ARIMA model vs the Holt-Winters.

Reviewing the ACF's of the residual confirm the lags at which this correlation is taking place within the residuals. It is within the confidence intervals so can be used for forecasting but should be invetsigated further.

Given our model was only based on historical demand data and we are dealing with daily sales we expect some level of information to be missing as many other macroeconomic or social factors could drive the impact of sales for our chosen location.

The out of sample performance measured through RMSE was 39. for the Holt-Winters model and 36 for the ARIMA model. I decided to choose the model with the lowest RMSE not MAPE or MSE as this takes the average of individual errors squared, so always positive and then transforms them back to the unit in question so for our problem this is ounces. In demand forecasting having an indication of the buffer in which the forecast may be incorrect enables for far more effective planning thorughout the supply chain.

If I had more time I would perform some bias correction techniques as choose the box cox transformation instead of log.

Appendix 1:¶

Data Transformation¶

Item 1) pos_ordersales and menuitems table dates

All days are 15 Months are (3,4,5,6) but all years range from 1930,1931,2000-2029. Assume that given data extract is form early March 2015 to 06/15/2015 that month is correct but day = year and year equals last two digits of current day.

Item 2) Create key between menuitem and menu_items tables called id_plu Concatinating menu_items.PLU menu_items.MenuItemId Concatinating menuitems.PLU with menuitems.Id

Item 3) Ingredients table PortionUOMTypeID - change to integer to match portion_uom_types.PortionUOMTypeID

Item 4) Remove stores not ID:46673

Data Modelling¶

Core Recipe

SELECT * FROM POS_ORDERSALE
LEFT JOIN MENUITEM ON
POS_ORDERSALE.MDKKEY_ORDERSALE = MENUITEM.MDKKEY_ORDERSALE
LEFT JOIN MENU_ITEMS ON
MENUITEMS.ID_PLU = MENU_ITEMS.ID_PLU
LEFT JOIN RECIPES ON
MENU_ITEMS.RECIPEID = RECIPES.RECIPEID
LEFT JOIN RECIPE_INGREDIENT_ASSIGNMENTS ON
RECIPES.RECIPED = RECIPES_INGREDIENT_ASSIGNMENT.RECIPEID
LEFT JOIN INGREDIENTS ON
RECIPES_INGREDIENT_ASSIGNMENT.INGREDIENTID = INGREDIENTS.INGREDIENTID
LEFT JOIN PORTION_UOM_TYPES ON
INGREDIENTS.PORTIONUOMTYPEID = PORTION_UOM_TYPES..PORTIONUOMTYPEID

Calculated Total Demand by menuitem.quantity * recipe_ingrtedient_assignments.quantity grouping by pos_ordersale date and ingredient = lettuce

Sub Recipes
SELECT * FROM POS_ORDERSALE
LEFT JOIN MENUITEM ON
POS_ORDERSALE.MDKKEY_ORDERSALE = MENUITEM.MDKKEY_ORDERSALE
LEFT JOIN MENU_ITEMS ON
MENUITEMS.ID_PLU = MENU_ITEMS.ID_PLU
LEFT JOIN RECIPES ON
MENU_ITEMS.RECIPEID = RECIPES.RECIPEID
LEFT JOIN RECIPE_SUB_RECIPE_ASSIGNMENTS ON
RECIPE.RECIPEID = RECIPE_SUB_RECIPE_ASSIGNMENTS.SUBRECIPEDID
LEFT JOIN SUB_RECIPES ON
RECIPE_SUB_RECIPE_ASSIGNMENTS.SUBRECIPEDID = SUB_RECIPES.SUBRECIPEID
LEFT JOIN INGREDIENTS ON
SUBRECIPES.INGREDIENTID = INGREDIENTS.INGREDIENTID
LEFT JOIN PORTION_UOM_TYPES ON
INGREDIENTS.PORTIONUOMTYPEID = PORTION_UOM_TYPES..PORTIONUOMTYPEID

Calculated Total Demand by menuitem.quantity recipe_ingrtedient_assignments.quantity recipe_sub_recipe_assignments.factor grouping by pos_ordersale date and ingredient = lettuce.

Combined these two documents and then used an excel Pivot table to get the total demand for lettuce for core and sub recipes which was validated against Jihua's sample lettuce dataset.
